Understanding the react based project structure as a backend developer
React-Scripts helps to build and start out react project.
React-router-dom allows the frontend to have the routes of its own for example /upcoming or /history in the given NASA mission control
dashboard.
React-dom allows our react code to make use of the document object model because our application is the web application and the DOM
is the object that browser use to store the current page that we are viewing.
Workflow of the provided React Frontend
Public folder contains Index.html which contains the main web view that is rendered by React app. I has a element with 'root' id.
The index.js contains the code that tells which component is rendered using the ReactDOM using the ids of elements. Here the root id
element will load the App component which is described in the App.js.
App.js is the main entry point for our application.
In the pages folder we have all the pages for our front-end application. It has the AppLayout page along with other pages elements.
Then there are the hooks, the hooks folder contains all the custom hooks required for our projects. The hooks are the special function
defined to accomplish a certain task in our React app.
Models vs Controllers vs Routers
Why controllers and routers in same folder but the models in the different folder?
Because:
There is one to one relation with the routers and the controllers. The planets controller is only used by the planets routers, and
the routers only call the functions inside the respective controllers. But the model can be used in different way by many different routers
and the controllers. Models represent the similar data. where the controllers and routers might use the combined models(data) to represent
them as the collection. For eg the stars model can be used to represent the constellations router and controllers.
Models works directly with data and contain data access functions, controllers use the data access functions irrespective of how the data
is being stored. Models.controllers and views correspond to data access layer,business logic and user interface resp. in layered architecture.
See also: Saperation of Concerns
Scripting for running Client and Server together
In the command line: use --prefix <foldername> at last of command to run inside a folder.
use && in between commands to execute one after another.
use & in between commands to execute at the same time.
Inside the scripts object in package.json of root for client and server
"install-server":"npm install --prefix server" ,
"install-client":"npm install --prefix client",
"install":"npm install --prefix server && npm install --prefix client" ,
"server":"npm start --prefix server",
"client":"npm start --prefix client",
"watch": "npm start server && npm run client",
"test": "npm run test --prefix server && npm run test --prefix client"
Running Frontend and Backend in same port in Production (Build)
Note: should use the cors middleware for getting response to frontend from different port
For that we must build our react project to a single build folder which is optimized for production.
npm run build
This creates the build folder with production ready project, but if we build within the server folder we can serve our frontend also via
same port or address. For that we can use BUILD_PATH=./server/public in the build script of react package.json.
Morgan logging middleware package
Logs streaming: The morgan provides the functionality to send logs to streams like a file or online log service.
Log rotation: Sending logs to new files everyday or every hour. Because in large production servers there are 1000s of requests in a second.
So the server hard disk could be full causing server crash.
Formats for Logging/Predefined formats: Choose what to save like date or http method. Predefined formats have commonly used formats.
Javascript's Maps
Maps in javascript are the key value pairs that can be used to represent any kind of data accordingly, not like objects we can use functions
and different other data types as key value pairs.
More here
Some Javascript functions
Array.from() Converts array-like or iterable objects (like a Map, Set, String, or arguments) into a real Array.
map.values() Returns an iterator of the values in a Map object, in insertion order.
array.sort() Converts elements to strings and sorts in ascending Unicode order.
or,
You can pass a comparison function for numerical or custom sorting. Negative return value means a before b. To memorize this,
remember that (a, b) => a - b sorts numbers in ascending order.
Any frontend that contains html 5 history api and epecially pushstate() function for routing, can be handled using wildcard parameters
route. Now after express 5 we need name of wildcards too eg '/*name'
Fig. Layered Architecture in SE
Object.assign() is a JavaScript method used to copy the values of all enumerable own properties from one or more source objects to a
target object. It returns the modified target object.
const target = { a: 1 };
const source = { b: 2, c: 3 };
const result = Object.assign(target, source);
console.log(result); // { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 }
console.log(target); // { a: 1, b: 2, c: 3 } — target is modified
Checking Dates
Use toString() function it return "Invalid Date" string if the date is invalid.
Use isNan() function, this function checks if the value is number or not. It returns true if it is value not a number. It works for date as
the valueOf() function on dates returns number so the condition is "false".
Note: isNaN() calls the isNan(date.valueOf()) function for objects, even if we dont call. So for dates it returns Unix timestamp which is
number.
